subsystem-promote-and-daemon-guard.value:
Two patterns from PR #112 (always-on scheduling infra, Phase 1):

(1) Subsystem promotion: when a subsystem initially housed under one feature (e.g. src/dashboard/scheduler.js) grows to serve the whole mesh, relocate it to a dedicated module (e.g. src/schedule/). Use `git mv` — behavior-preserving; repoint all importers and test imports. The old path becomes dead code the moment importers are updated; do not leave it in place. Applies to: any service initially placed under a feature dir that becomes cross-cutting infrastructure.

(2) Always-on daemon guard: a daemon that starts long-running services must guard against single-pass modes:
```
if (!opts.once && !opts.selftest) {
  const svc = createService(meshRoot);
  svc.start();
  process.on('SIGTERM', () => svc.stop());
  process.on('SIGINT',  () => svc.stop());
}
```
Why: --once and --selftest are sweep/health-check invocations that must complete and exit. A scheduler or background poller started in those modes outlives the sweep, leaks process resources, and interferes with subsequent test runs.

Test coverage: (a) selftest mode → service.start() is NOT called, process exits 0; (b) normal mode → service.start() called, SIGTERM triggers stop(). See test/daemon-scheduler.test.js (PR #112).

(3) Read-only aggregation API: expose per-agent state as a mesh-wide read-only endpoint (GET /api/schedules → {schedulerOwner, jobs:[...]}). The endpoint is a view, not a store — data lives in per-agent files. Use injected deps for hermetic testing. Provenance: PR #112 (2026-06-18).

gha-cron-throttle-use-daemon-builtin.value:
When a sweep must complete within minutes, not hours:

(1) Register a daemon builtin in the target agent's schedule.json: {"id": "automerge-sweep", "kind": "builtin", "name": "automerge-sweep", "enabled": true, "every": 10}. The daemon scheduler dispatches by kind — no LLM spawn.

(2) Register the function in the daemon's builtin registry (scripts/dev-society-daemon.mjs):
  builtins['automerge-sweep'] = async () => {
    if (!enabled) return {status:'ok', output:'disabled'};
    await runAutomergeSweep({...});
    return {status:'ok'};
  };
Gate on the sweep's kill-switch env var (AUTOMERGE_ENABLED). Return {status:'ok'} explicitly — void breaks onJobResult (see scheduler-builtin-return-shape).

(3) Keep the GHA cron workflow as a cold-start backstop. Share the same runSweep/isAutoMergeable logic — no duplication between daemon and GHA paths.

(4) Test: assert (a) daemon registers the builtin name; (b) builtin gates on the env flag; (c) schedule.json has the job at every ≤10; (d) existing GHA cron schedule remains present.

Red flag: PRs idle for hours while the automerge workflow claims `*/15` → GHA cron is throttled; migrate sweep to daemon builtin. Provenance: PR #231 (2026-06-20).

gitignored-generated-file-absent-test.value:
Pattern: testing doctor-generated / tool-generated files that are gitignored.

(1) NEVER assert 'file must not exist'. Gitignored files are absent on clean CI clones but present on deployed instances where the generator ran. Result: CI=green, production=red (env-flaky).

(2) Assert the REAL invariant: IF the file exists, it must match the expected schema/content:
  if (existsSync(path)) {
    const cfg = JSON.parse(readFileSync(path, 'utf8'));
    // e.g. assert only the ask-safe peer-bridge is present; no mutating servers
    assert.ok(cfg.mcpServers?.agentmesh_peerbridge);
    assert.strictEqual(Object.keys(cfg.mcpServers).length, 1);
  }
  // No else — absence is vacuously correct

(3) The stated invariant is almost never 'file must not exist' — it is a safety property about the file's CONTENTS (e.g. 'no mutating servers', 'only ask-safe bridge'). Test that.

(4) Env-flaky signature: test passes in hermetic CI (npm test) but fails under MIR --run-suites (real deploy). Primary suspect: an absence assertion on a gitignored, generator-produced artifact.

(5) When fixing one such test, audit sibling gitignored files (*.mcp.json, .agent/*.json) for the same pattern — absence tests cluster around framework-generated artifacts.

Provenance: PR #300 (2026-06-21).

mir-rolling-window-median-baseline.value:
Apply when adding baseline comparison to any time-series metric with high coefficient of variation (CV > ~0.3) — typically ratio metrics like cost-per-turn, tokens-per-run, latency-per-token.

(1) Carry history per finding: in the baseline record (mir.json), append the current metric value to the per-finding `history` array, capped to `trendN` entries:
  newHistory[f.id] = [...priorValues, f.metric.value].slice(-trendN);

(2) Two-tier baseline selection:
  if (priorValues.length >= MEDIAN_WINDOW_MIN) {  // 3 is the Phase-0 constant
    base = median(priorValues.slice(-trendN));     // outlier-resistant
  } else {
    base = prevFindings.get(f.id)?.metric.value;   // cold-start fallback
  }

(3) Why median over mean: a single anomalous run (network latency, model jitter) inflates the mean and triggers a false regression alarm on the next normal run. Median is insensitive to a single outlier in a window of trendN. Heuristic: if σ/mean > 0.3, single-previous-value is too noisy — switch to median.

(4) Cold-start invariant: MEDIAN_WINDOW_MIN = 3 means runs 1 and 2 always use §10 single-previous. Never compute a median on fewer than 3 points; the result would be less stable than the value itself.

(5) Spec-conformance guard: when an implementation decision was previously deferred, lock it with a test that reads both the spec and the code:
  const spec = readFileSync('docs/.../design.md', 'utf8');
  assert.ok(!spec.includes('v2-deferred'), '§11 must be in v1');
  const code = readFileSync('src/.../baseline.js', 'utf8');
  assert.ok(code.includes('median('), 'median must be in baseline.js');
A future PR re-deferring the feature must also update the spec — CI enforces the coupling.

(6) Required test matrix: cold-start fallback, median smoothing (outlier suppression), real regression detection (genuine δ), outlier recovery (metric returns to normal), history GC (trendN eviction), spec-conformance guard. Without all six, a refactor can silently remove cold-start safety or windowing.

Provenance: PR #330 (2026-06-21), closes #324.

render-nested-api-guard-leaf-scalar.value:
Apply whenever a dashboard renderer reads a field from an API response that may be a nested object rather than a scalar.

(1) Type-guard before drilling: never assume a value is scalar because it maps to a 'number-like' concept (tokens, cost, metrics). Check typeof before accessing nested paths:
  const tot = s.tokens && typeof s.tokens === 'object'
    ? (s.tokens.total ?? s.tokens)
    : null;
  if (tot && typeof tot === 'object') {
    if (typeof tot.costUsd === 'number') add('Cost (24h)', '$' + tot.costUsd.toFixed(2));
    const io = (typeof tot.input === 'number' || typeof tot.output === 'number')
      ? (tot.input || 0) + (tot.output || 0) : null;
    add('Tokens in+out', io != null ? io.toLocaleString() : null);
  }

(2) Flat-shape tolerance: if the API may also return a simpler/flat shape, add a typeof guard on the flat path. Only pass scalars to the render function (String(), template literals, DOM text):
  if (!rows.length) {
    const flat = (k, label) => {
      if (typeof s[k] === 'string' || typeof s[k] === 'number') add(label, s[k]);
    };
    flat('totalCost', 'Cost (24h)'); // scalar fallback only
  }

(3) Test with the REAL API shape: a test stub with tokens:42 passes even when the nested-object bug is live, because String(42) works. Tests must mirror the actual server response shape:
  const daily = { summary: { tokens: { total: { input: 100, output: 200, costUsd: 0.50 } }, prs: { merged: ['pr1'], openNow: 2 } } };
  assert.ok(!JSON.stringify(summarizeStatus({ daily })).includes('[object Object]'));

(4) Red flag: '[object Object]' in UI output always means a plain object was coerced to string. Audit the render path for any implicit String() or template-literal conversion of a non-primitive. Victims: tokens.total.*, cost.usd, stats.value, any field with a sub-key in the schema.

(5) Rule: add() / render() helpers should only ever call String() on primitives. Make the helper itself defensive: if (val != null && val !== '' && typeof val !== 'object') rows.push({ label, value: String(val) }).

Provenance: PR #373 (2026-06-21), src/dashboard/public/mobile/app.js summarizeStatus.

ios-tts-gesture-unlock.value:
Apply when adding TTS (Text-to-Speech) to a mobile PWA or web app that uses fetch-based async flows:

(1) GESTURE-UNLOCK PATTERN: iOS Safari requires `speechSynthesis.speak()` to be triggered — directly or via a short chain — from a user gesture. A post-fetch callback is NOT a user gesture. Fix: call `engine.unlock()` inside a tap/click handler. `unlock()` primes a silent (volume 0) utterance in that gesture, satisfying iOS's requirement for the rest of the session. Make it idempotent (guard with `if (this._unlocked) return`).

```js
unlock() {
  if (this._unlocked || !window.speechSynthesis) return;
  const u = new SpeechSynthesisUtterance(' ');
  u.volume = 0;
  window.speechSynthesis.speak(u);
  this._unlocked = true;
}
```

(2) WHERE TO CALL UNLOCK: call on the user action that initiates voice (mic tap, voice-toggle click). This gives the engine its gesture budget before the async reply arrives. The unlock is a one-time session setup, not a per-utterance call.

(3) READBACK TOGGLE: pair the gesture-unlock with a 🔊 'read replies aloud' toggle (persisted in `localStorage`). This makes reply-voice a first-class opt-in visible to users who don't know to tap the mic. When the toggle is on, ALL replies are read aloud (including typed turns). Read back when `speakReplies || lastWasVoice`.

(4) TOGGLE OFF: cancel in-flight TTS with `window.speechSynthesis.cancel()` when the toggle is switched off mid-reply.

(5) TEST IMPLICATIONS: the unlock is a behavior the test fake must model. In unit tests: assert `unlock()` calls `speak()` once with a silent utterance, is idempotent (second call is no-op), and is a no-op when `speechSynthesis` is absent.

(6) PATTERN GENERALIZES: the gesture-budget trick applies to any browser API that requires a synchronous user-gesture touch before async use. `AudioContext` also requires `context.resume()` in a gesture before async playback. Prime in the tap handler; consume asynchronously.

Related: ios-cookie-redirect-drop (other iOS Safari async surprises), pwa-voice-swappable-adapter (the adapter interface this unlock slot into). Provenance: PR #391 (2026-06-22).

perf-baseline-compare-before-update.value:
Apply whenever adding baseline-comparison drift detection to any metric store:

(1) Cold-start guard:
  if (!baseline[cell]) {
    baseline[cell] = currentP50;  // establish
    emit({ severity: "info", msg: "baseline established" });
    return;  // no regression finding on first observation
  }

(2) Compare-then-update ordering (mandatory sequencing):
  const delta = (current - baseline[cell]) / baseline[cell];  // compare first
  if (isAdverse(metric, delta) && Math.abs(delta) > warnBudget) emit(finding);
  baseline[cell] = rollingP50([...history, current]);  // update AFTER

(3) Direction-aware adversity:
  function isAdverse(metric, delta) {
    return higherIsBetter(metric) ? delta < 0 : delta > 0;
  }

Complements mir-rolling-window-median-baseline (noise-resistant median selection) and mir-slow-drift-trend-gate (slow cumulative drift). The three lessons are additive: robust median → compare → trend trend-check.

Provenance: PR #416 (2026-06-22), closes #412.

implicit-set-subset-assert-or-derive.value:
Apply when two parallel constant sets must maintain A ⊆ B for a correctness invariant (every trigger-state must be in the strip-set; every allowed command must be in the safe-set). Silent failure mode: developers add to A independently of B; no comment links them; the invariant silently breaks in production, re-introducing bugs that had been fixed.

Two options (prefer B; pair with a hermetic test either way):

(A) Module-load assertion (runtime tripwire):
  for (const s of RECONCILE_STATES) {
    if (!LIFECYCLE_STATES.includes(s))
      throw new Error(`RECONCILE_STATES has '${s}' not in LIFECYCLE_STATES — strip-all violated`);
  }
  Pro: minimal diff; error names the offending element; fires at daemon startup AND test import.
  Con: two lists remain hand-maintained; catches drift at import, not at PR time.

(B) Structural derivation (recommended):
  const RECONCILE_STATES = LIFECYCLE_STATES.filter(l => IN_FLIGHT_SET.has(l) || l === APPROVED);
  Pro: A ⊆ B is guaranteed by construction — no assertion can be forgotten; adding a lifecycle state and wanting it to trigger reconcile is a single edit.
  Con: membership is less transparent than a literal list.

Hermetic test (required regardless of option):
  assert(RECONCILE_STATES.every(s => LIFECYCLE_STATES.includes(s)), 'A⊆B invariant violated');
  CI gates every PR — the module-load guard catches it live; the test catches it before merge.

The two options are not mutually exclusive: derive (B) makes the invariant structural, and the hermetic test still guards against a future refactor that re-introduces a hand-maintained list.

Signal that this pattern is needed: a code review noting 'X ⊆ Y is a hand-maintained silent dependency' — encode immediately, not as a follow-up ticket. PR #435 reviewer found exactly this; Issue #442 captured it; PR #445 spec formalised both options.

Generalises to: trigger-states ⊆ strip-states; allowed-commands ⊆ safe-commands; reconcile-labels ⊆ lifecycle-labels; any two parallel lists where one must be a subset of the other. Related: [[lifecycle-strip-all-on-terminal-close]] (PR #435 introduced the strip-all; PR #445 hardened its invariant). Provenance: PR #445 (2026-06-23) / Issue #442.

brain-runtime-failure-as-data.value:
When integrating a new brain runtime (Gemini or any future provider), two structural requirements apply beyond run-record field names (see multi-brain-run-record-parity):

(1) WRAP THE BRAIN-LOOP IN TRY/CATCH — NEVER LET EXCEPTIONS ESCAPE.
The main brain-loop section must be enclosed in try/catch and return a structured status:'error' Task on failure. Node.js terminates the process on unhandled rejections. In a long-running A2A server, one transient API error without a catch takes the entire server down. The mesh's "failure is data, not an exception" invariant (PROJECT.md) applies to ALL brain implementations, not just the canonical Claude path.

Pattern:
  try {
    const result = await runBrainLoop(...)
    return buildTask({ status: 'done', ...result })
  } catch (err) {
    runLog.write({ event: 'error', error: err.message })
    return buildTask({ status: 'error', summary: err.message })
  }

Confirm the caller (voice ingress or other) already handles non-COMPLETED Tasks with a fixed fallback before relying on degraded-gracefully behavior.

(2) THREAD BRAIN USAGE THROUGH TO THE RUN RECORD.
The brain function (runBrainLoop or equivalent) must return the token/cost usage block and the outer caller must carry it to the run record and Task result. Silently dropping usage leaves usage:null — indistinguishable from a zero-turn run and hides real API spend from the observability stack. Match the Claude path: cost, tokens, and latency all reach the run record.

(3) TEST COVERAGE FROM DAY ONE.
Add a test for "brain that throws → status:'error' Task returned, never an unhandled rejection" on initial integration — the crash path is not exercised by any happy-path test. PR #622 added this test as the crash repro.

Companion: multi-brain-run-record-parity (PR #620) — run-record field names.
